            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this short-term capital gains tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                In the U.S., <strong>short-term capital gains</strong> (assets
                held for one year or less) are taxed at your
                <strong>ordinary income tax rates</strong>. That means they use
                the same tax brackets as your wages, interest, and other regular
                income.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator estimates your federal short-term capital gains
                tax by:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Loading the IRS ordinary income tax brackets for your
                  <strong>tax year</strong> and <strong>filing status</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Estimating your <strong>taxable income</strong> with and
                  without your short-term gains.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Calculating total tax in each case using a progressive bracket
                  calculation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Showing the <strong>extra tax</strong> caused by your gains
                  and the <strong>effective tax rate</strong> on those gains.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Core idea</p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><code>I</code> = taxable income before gains</li>
                  <li>
                    <code>G</code> = net short-term capital gains (can be
                    negative)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <code>T(x)</code> = tax on taxable income
                    <code>x</code> using the ordinary brackets
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Tax without gains:</strong> <code>T(I)</code></li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Tax with gains:</strong> <code>T(I + G)</code>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Extra tax from gains:</strong>
                    <code>ΔT = T(I + G) - T(I)</code>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Effective tax rate on gains:</strong>
                    <code>ΔT / G</code> (if <code>G &gt; 0</code>)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h2>What counts as a short-term capital gain?</h2>
              <p>
                A gain is usually <strong>short-term</strong> if you held the
                asset for <strong>one year or less</strong> before selling it.
                The holding period typically starts the day after you acquire
                the asset and ends on the day you sell it.
              </p>
              <p>Common examples of short-term gains include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Stock or ETF trades closed within a year.</li>
                <li>Cryptocurrency bought and sold within a year.</li>
                <li>
                  Real estate flips held for less than a year (subject to other
                  rules).
                </li>
                <li>Short-term mutual fund holdings.</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Short-term vs. long-term capital gains</h2>
              <p>
                The key difference is the <strong>holding period</strong> and
                the <strong>tax rate</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Short-term capital gains</strong> (held ≤ 1 year) are
                  taxed at your
                  <strong>ordinary income tax rates</strong> (10%–37% depending
                  on income and filing status).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Long-term capital gains</strong> (held &gt; 1 year)
                  usually benefit from <strong>preferential rates</strong> (0%,
                  15%, or 20% for most assets, plus possible surtaxes).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Because short-term gains are taxed like regular income, frequent
                trading can push you into
                <strong>higher tax brackets</strong>. The calculator shows the
                <strong>top marginal rate</strong> reached after adding your
                gains.
              </p>

              <h2>Understanding the results</h2>
              <h3>Total tax with and without gains</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator computes your estimated federal tax bill in two
                scenarios:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Without gains</strong> – using only your taxable
                  income before gains.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>With gains</strong> – using your taxable income plus
                  net short-term gains.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The difference between these two amounts is the
                <strong>extra tax</strong> caused by your short-term gains.
              </p>

              <h3>Effective tax rate on your gains</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>effective tax rate</strong> on your short-term gains
                is:
              </p>
              <p class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >Effective rate = Extra tax from gains ÷ Net short-term
                  gains</code
                >
              </p>
              <p>
                This can be lower than your
                <strong>top marginal bracket</strong> if some of your gains fall
                into lower brackets.
              </p>

              <h3>Top marginal rate reached</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator also shows the
                <strong>highest bracket</strong> that applies to your income
                after gains. This is the rate that applies to your
                <em>last dollar</em> of income, including gains.
              </p>

              <h2>Tips for managing short-term capital gains tax</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Hold investments longer when possible.</strong>
                  Waiting until you cross the one-year mark can convert a
                  short-term gain into a long-term gain, often lowering the tax
                  rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use tax-loss harvesting carefully.</strong>
                  Realizing losses can offset gains, but be aware of wash-sale
                  rules and other limitations.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider tax-advantaged accounts.</strong>
                  Trading inside IRAs, 401(k)s, and similar accounts can
                  or avoid capital gains tax entirely, depending on the account
                  type and withdrawals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Watch your brackets.</strong>
                  Large short-term gains in a high-income year can push you into
                  a higher marginal bracket. Spreading gains across years may
                  reduce your overall tax burden.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is designed for quick planning and education.
                It:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Uses current federal ordinary income tax brackets for 2024 and
                  an estimated set for 2025.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Assumes your input is <strong>taxable income</strong> (after
                  deductions), unless you choose to approximate deductions.
                </li>
                <li>Ignores state and local income taxes.</li>
                <li>
                  Does not handle every special rule (e.g., collectibles,
                  Section 1256 contracts, wash sales, NIIT).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not replace professional tax advice or official IRS
                  tools.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For complex situations—such as large real estate transactions,
                business asset sales, or multi-year planning— consider working
                with a qualified tax professional.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Short-term capital gains tax FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is short-term capital gains tax?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Short-term capital gains tax is the tax you pay on profits
                    from selling investments you held for one year or less. In
                    the U.S., these gains are taxed at your ordinary income tax
                    rates, using the same brackets that apply to wages and other
                    income.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How are short-term capital gains calculated?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    First, you calculate your gain for each sale: sale price
                    minus your cost basis (what you paid, plus certain
                    adjustments). Then you net all your short-term gains and
                    losses for the year. The resulting net short-term gain is
                    added to your other taxable income and taxed using the
                    ordinary income tax brackets for your filing status and tax
                    year.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can short-term capital losses reduce my taxes?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Yes. Short-term capital losses first offset short-term
                    capital gains. If you still have a net loss, it can offset
                    other capital gains and then up to the IRS-allowed amount of
                    ordinary income each year, with any remaining loss carried
                    forward. This calculator lets you enter a negative gain
                    amount to see how a net short-term loss may reduce your
                    estimated tax.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Does this include state or local capital gains tax?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    No. This tool estimates <strong>federal</strong> short-term
                    capital gains tax only. Many states tax capital gains as
                    ordinary income, but rates and rules vary. Check your
                    state’s tax authority or consult a tax professional for a
                    full picture of your total tax liability.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is this calculator suitable for real estate and business
                    sales?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    It can provide a rough estimate of the federal tax impact if
                    the gain is treated as a short-term capital gain, but real
                    estate and business asset sales often involve additional
                    rules (depreciation recapture, exclusions, installment
                    sales, etc.). For those situations, use this as a starting
                    point and then consult a tax professional.
                  </p>
                </details>
